  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal offense in most jurisdictions and typically falls under criminal legislation. It is considered a serious financial crime that involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money by passing it through legitimate businesses or financial systems to make it appear legal. \n\nKey points about money laundering in criminal law include:\n\n1. It is a criminal offense in most countries\n2. Penalties can include significant fines and imprisonment\n3. It is often associated with other predicate crimes like:\n- Drug trafficking\n- Fraud\n- Organized crime\n- Corruption\n\nMany countries have specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations designed to prevent, detect, and prosecute such financial crimes.",
